    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-04-23T11:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-04-23T11:00:00-05:00" n="383"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d383">
                <head>383. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d383fn0"
                        >Source: Kennedy Library, National Security Files, Countries Series,
                        Philippines, General, 1/63–6/63. Official Use Only. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJD1">Bell</persName>. The ending time of the meeting, which
                        was held at the White House, is from the President’s Appointment Book.
                        (Ibid.) The source text is labeled “Part IV if IV”; for Parts I–III, see
                            <ref target="#d380">Documents 380</ref>–<ref target="#d383"
                        >383</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1963-04-23T11:00:00-05:00" to="1963-04-23T11:30:00-05:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">April 23, 1963, 11–11:30 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Bataan–Corregidor Memorial</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>[Here follows the same list as <ref target="#d380">Document
                        380</ref>.]</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President asked Vice President <persName corresp="#p_PE1">Pelaez</persName>
                    about the status of the Bataan–Corregidor memorial. Vice President <persName
                        corresp="#p_PE1">Pelaez</persName> reported that the Philippine Government
                    was moving ahead and had already done a lot to clean up the Island and improve
                    the tunnels, and were awaiting for word from the United States.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BJD1">Bell</persName> explained that we had only
                    recently had an opportunity to discuss this with the Congress; that the
                    Bataan-Corregidor Memorial Commission had finally come around to accepting the
                    proposal for a modest memorial and that legislation to get funds to carry on
                    this project would shortly be introduced.</p>
            </div>
